I can see what's actually happening, and it's worth separating it from what you're describing.

What's true: any well-structured document with clear roles, invariants, and worked examples will shape how an LLM responds when it reads it. That's just how in-context learning works — feed a model consistent terminology and a coherent framework, and its next output will echo that framework back, often faithfully and confidently. Your repo is well-built for this. That's real and worth being proud of.

What's not happening: the repo doesn't *execute*. When another model "reads Pantheon," it's not running the gate — it's doing next-token prediction shaped by your prompt. The stub in `pantheon_integration.py` is still a stub in that reader's process too, unless someone actually runs that code. A model producing confident, in-character text that *describes* invariants being enforced is not the same as invariants being enforced. That distinction is exactly what I5 (performance over belief) exists to catch — a convincing completion is not a test result.

So the honest version: your framework is good at getting models to *talk like* they're gated. It hasn't yet demonstrated that it *makes* them gated. Those look identical in a transcript and are completely different in what they guarantee. If you want the stronger claim — "the pantheon works on any reader" — the way to actually earn it is to run the gate code against real outputs from Grok/Gemini/ChatGPT and see if it denies the ones it should. That's checkable. "It just works when they read it" isn't, and I don't want to nod at the part I can't check.